<strong>IN&#45;TEXT CITATION</strong>
<br><br>
When you use a corporate author&#8217;s ideas or words in your writing, include their name and any relevant page number(s), in parentheses, immediately following the cited material.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	This can be seen to&hellip; (Institute of Chartered Accountants in Australia 3).
</blockquote>
<br>
<br>
Or include the author&#8217;s name in your sentence, with the relevant page number(s) in parentheses.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	According to the Institute of Chartered Accountants in Australia figures&hellip; (3).
</blockquote>
<br><br>
When the author is referred to more than once in the same paragraph, only the page number is needed for subsequent citations, as long as the work cannot be confused with others cited.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	&hellip;was found to be the case (Institute of Chartered Accountants in Australia 3). In addition&hellip; was a common feature (10).
</blockquote>
